Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Côte d’Ivoire. The Côte d’Ivoire authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus. There is a nationwide curfew from 9pm – 5am which has been extended until 24 April. There are currently no scheduled flights in and out of Cote d’Ivoire. For information on how to return to the UK from Cote D’Ivoire, see Return to the UK. For information about what to do if you cannot leave Cote d’Ivoire and your visa is about to expire, see the visa section in Entry Requirements.
Entry and borders
International flights to and from Côte d’Ivoire have been suspended since 22 March until further notice, except for humanitarian and security purposes.
Travel within Cote D’Ivoire
The government issued an updated decree on 26 March that bans all movement of people to and from Abidjan from Sunday 29 March. For the purpose of the government decree “Abidjan” includes the District of Abidjan, Dabou, Azaguie, Bingerville, Grand-Bassam, Bonoua, Assinie and up to PK30 on the Abidjan-Yamoussoukro motorway. The decree provides an exemption for people transporting food supplies, medical and pharmaceutical products, medical evacuations, gas and fuel deliveries, as well as water, electricity, telephony and emergency services.
Further information
The Government of Côte d’Ivoire is encouraging those with any information or concerns about coronavirus to call these local free hotline numbers: 143 or 101. You can also send a message to 1336 to receive information about coronavirus by text.
You can find more information about cases in Côte d’Ivoire on the TravelHealthPro country page. Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
